5b3.clickbait: Task-based AGIs don't need unlimited cognitive and material powers to carry out their Tasks; which means their powers can potentially be limited.

5l.title: Complexity of value
5l.clickbait: There's no simple way to describe the goals we want Artificial Intelligences to want.

5s.title: Value alignment problem

6w.title: Task-directed AGI
6w.clickbait: An advanced AI that's meant to pursue a series of limited-scope goals given it by the user.  In Bostrom's terminology, a Genie.

7g0.title: Non-adversarial principle
7g0.clickbait: At no point in constructing an Artificial General Intelligence should we construct a computation that tries to hurt us, and then try to stop it from hurting us.

7g1.title: Sufficiently advanced Artificial Intelligence
7g1.clickbait: 'Sufficiently advanced Artificial Intelligences' are AIs with enough 'advanced agent properties' that we start needing to do 'AI alignment' to them.

7tf.title: Minimality principle
7tf.clickbait: The first AGI ever built should save the world in a way that requires the least amount of the least dangerous cognition.

7v7.title: Understandability principle
7v7.clickbait: The more you understand what the heck is going on inside your AI, the safer you are.

7vb.title: Effability principle
7vb.clickbait: You are safer the more you understand the inner structure of how your AI thinks; the better you can describe the relation of smaller pieces of the AI's thought process.

7vf.title: Cognitive domain
7vf.clickbait: An allegedly compact unit of knowledge, such that ideas inside the unit interact mainly with each other and less with ideas in other domains.

7w5.title: Environmental goals
7w5.clickbait: The problem of having an AI want outcomes that are out in the world, not just want direct sense events.

7wl.title: Aligning an AGI adds significant development time
7wl.clickbait: Aligning an advanced AI foreseeably involves extra code and extra testing and not being able to do everything the fastest way, so it takes longer.
7wl.text:
# Definition

True in your belief, if you believe that, comparing reasonably attainable development paths for...

- An [2v aligned] [7g1 advanced AI] created by a responsible project that is hurrying where it can, but still being careful enough to maintain a success probability greater than 25%
- An unaligned unlimited [41l superintelligence] produced by a project cutting all possible corners

...where otherwise both projects have access to the same ideas or discoveries in the field of AGI capabilities; then the first project would take *at least* 50% longer time to complete than the second project, or two years longer, whichever is less.

[toc:]

# Purpose

This page was written to address multiple questions who seem to have accepted the [1y Orthogonality thesis], but still mostly disbelieve it would take significantly longer to develop aligned AGI than unaligned AGI.

At present this page is an overview of possible places of disagreement, and may be selectively rather than fully expanded.

# Arguments

## Related propositions

Propositions feeding into this one include:

- (1a) [5l] (even as applied to a [minimum_pivotal_task])
- (1b) [7wm]

If questioner believes the negation of either of these, it would imply simple specifiability of a decision function loadable into an unlimited superintelligence.  This in turn would negate or greatly reduce the need for, e.g:

- (2a) [7g0 Non-adversarial design]
- (2b) [7tf Minimal design]
- (2c) [5b3 Limitation] of the AGI's abilities
- (2d) [7v7 Understandable design] or [transparency transparent elements] in any regard except the top-level preferences (and the [actual_effectiveness actual effectiveness] of those preferences within the AGI)

It's also worth checking whether any of these principles seem to questioner to *not* follow as requirements from the basic idea of value alignment being necessary and not trivially solvable by a simple algorithm.

## Outside view

It is normal, usual, and unsurprising for *at least* 50% increased development time to be required by strong versus minimal demands on *any one* of:

- (3a) safety when operating on humans
- (3b) robust behavior across new contexts
- (3c) robust behavior when experiencing strong forces
- (3d) reliable avoidance of even a single instance of a class of catastrophic failures
- (3e) resilience in the face of strong optimization pressures potentially leading code to traverse unusual execution paths
- (3f) conformance to complicated details of a user's desired system behavior

It would indeed be unusual--some project managers might call it *truly extraordinary* good fortune--if a system demanding *two or more* of these properties did *not* require at least 50% more development time compared to a system that didn't.

Obvious analogies include:

- Launching a space probe that cannot be corrected once launched, a deed which usually calls for extraordinary additional advance checking and testing
- Launching the simplest working rocket that will experience uncommonly great accelerations and forces, compared to building the simplest working airplane
- It would be far less expensive to design rockets if "the rocket explodes" were not a problem; most of the cost of a rocket is having the rocket not explode
- NASA managing to write almost entirely bug-free code for some projects at 100x the cost per line of code, using means that involved multiple reviews and careful lines of organizational approval for every aspect and element of the system
- The OpenBSD project to produce a secure operating system, which needed to constrain its code to be far more minimal than larger Linux projects, and probably added a lot more than 50% time per function point to approve each element of the secure code
- The difference in effort put forth by an amateur writing an encryption system they think is secure, versus the cryptographic ecosystem trying to ensure a channel is secure
- The real premium on safety for hospital equipment, as opposed to the bureaucratic premium on it, is probably still over 50% because it *does* involve legitimate additional testing to try to not kill the patient
- Surgeons probably legitimately require at least 50% longer to operate on humans than they would require to perform operations of analogous complexity on large plants it was okay to kill 10% of the time
- Even in the total absence of regulatory overhead, it seems legitimately harder to build a nuclear power plant that *usually* does not melt down, compared to a coal power plant (confirmable by the Soviet experience?)

Some of the particular standard ways in which systems with strong versus minimal demands on (3*)-properties *usually* require additional development time:

- (4a) Needing whole additional modules, universally enforced properties, or function points to meet the strong demand.
- (4b) Needing a more extended process of shaping in order to meet a complicated demand
- (4c) Legitimately requiring longer organizational paths to approve ideas, changes and commitments
- (4d) Longer and deeper test phases, both on whole systems and on local components or function points
- (4e) Not being able to deploy the fast or easy solution (that you could use at some particular choice point if you didn't need to worry about the rocket not exploding)
  - Constraints on materials or components (that require extra design work, compared to being able to toss in a wooden beam instead of carbon composite)

### Outside view on AI problems

Another relevant reference class is that things *having to do with AI* are often also more difficult than expected.  E.g. the story of computer vision being assigned to 2 undergrads over the summer, seems like a relevant case in point of "your uncorrected intuition has a directional bias in underestimating the amount of work required to implement cognitive properties and things having to do with AI, and you should correct that directional bias by revising your estimate upward".

Given a sufficiently advanced Artificial *General* Intelligence, we might get problems on the order of computer vision for free.  But the whole point of Orthogonality is that you do *not* get AI alignment for free with general intelligence; likewise identifying value-laden concepts doesn't come free with identifying natural empirical concepts.  We have *separate* AI work to do for alignment.  So the analogy to underestimating a narrow AI problem, in the early days before anyone has ever tried that problem, remains apposite.

## Inside view

While it is possible to build new systems that aren't 100% understood, and have them work, the successful ones were almost always greatly overengineered.  Some Roman bridges have stayed up two millennia later, which probably wasn't in the design requirements, so in that sense they turned out to be hugely overengineered, but we can't blame them.  It would have taken a much more precise art of engineering for them to design bridges that just barely didn't fall down.

If we get an aligned Task AGI *without* having solved for a really deep understanding of how to build exactly the right AGI with no extra parts or extra problems--and this must certainly be true on any scenario involving relatively short timescales--then we have to do all the things in order to have even a 25% chance of surviving, because we don't know which part of the system we really need to overengineer.

You don't know in advance that the O-Rings are the part of the Space Shuttle that's going to suddenly behave unexpectedly and threaten to fail, and you can't put in extra effort to armor only that part of the process.  You have to overengineer everything.

This suggests that even if you don't buy my particular laundry list below, whoever walks through this problem, conditioned on their eventual survival, will have shown up with *some* laundry list of precautions, including costly precautions, and they will (correctly) *not* imagine themselves able to survive based on some supposed "minimum necessary" precautions.

That said, here's a sample of some of the kinds of extra time costs that I imagine in concrete detail might be required:

- The AGI can only deploy internal optimization on small pieces of itself
- Everything to do with real alignment (as opposed to the AI having a reward button or being reinforcement-trained to 'obey orders' on some channel) is an additional set of function points
- You have to build new pieces of the system for transparency and monitoring, including notions like "There's actually a separatish AI over here that we built to inspect the first AI and check for problems, including having this AI trained on different data for safety-related concepts"
- There's a lot of [trusted](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trusted_system) function points where you can't just toss in an enormous deepnet because it wouldn't meet the [-transparency] or [7vb effability] requirements at that function point
- When somebody proposes a new optimization thingy, it has to be rejiggered to ensure it meets the top-to-bottom [4mn taskishness] requirement, and everyone has to stare at it to make sure it doesn't blow up the world somehow
- You can't run jobs on AWS because you don't trust Amazon with the code and you don't want to connect your AI to the goddamned Internet
- Some of your system designs rely on [major_monitored all 'major' events being monitored and all unseen events being 'minor'], and the major monitored events go through a human in the loop.  The humans in the loop are then a process rate-limiting factor and you can't just 'push the lever all the way up' on that line of investigation.
  - E.g., only 'major' goals can recruit subgoals across all known [7vf domains] and 'minor' goals only operate within a domain using limited cognitive resources.
- Deployment involves a *long conversation* with the AI about 'what do you expect to happen after you do X?' while other programmers are trying to look at passively transparent interpretations of the AI's thoughts while it's answering you
- The project has a much lower threshold for saying "wait, what the hell just happened, we need to stop melt and catch fire, not just try different patches until it seems to run again"
- One perhaps does a tad more testing

## Meta view

Despite the Inside View section above, this doesn't feel to me like a case where the conclusion is highly dependent on Eliezer-details.  *Anyone* with a concrete plan for aligning an AI is going to walk in with a list of plans and methods for safety, some of which require close inspection of parts, and constrain allowable designs, and just plain take more work.

I likewise can't see how, after [imagining oneself in the shoes](http://lesswrong.com/lw/j0/making_history_available/) of the early researchers tackling computer vision and 'commonsense reasoning' and 'natural-language processing', after vicariously experiencing the entirety of the history of AI, anyone could reasonably stagger back in *shocked and horrified surprise* upon encountering the completely unexpected fact of a weird new AI problem being kinda hard.  Even if you didn't visualize that particular obstacle in advance, you still have no right to be surprised.

I genuinely have some trouble figuring out what objection is standing in the way of accepting this proposition, granting Orthogonality and alignment not being completely trivial.  I literally don't know what to say next.

It feels to me like some basic aspect of what I consider to be cognitive realism is not being implemented.  Despite the dangers of [43h psychologizing], for purposes of oversharing I'm going to directly state some of what *feels to me* like it isn't there:

- (5a) Even if one feels intuitively optimistic about a project, one ought to expect in advance to run into difficulties not immediately obvious.  You should not be in a state of mind where tomorrow's surprises are a lot more likely to be unpleasant than pleasant; this is [-predictable_updating].  The person telling you your hopeful software project is going to take longer than 2 weeks does not need to be able to tell you in advance exactly what is going to go wrong.  It *feels like* "elementary correction for optimistic bias 101" is missing.
- (5b) It *feels like* this is being put into a mental bucket of "futuristic scenarios" rather than "software development projects", and is being processed as something something pessimistic future versus normal future something something.  Instead of "If I ask a project manager for a ginormous new feature that impacts every aspect of the software project, can it get done in just 10% more time than a project that's eliminating that feature and cutting all the corners?"
- (5c) I similarly recall the old experiment in which students named their "best case" scenarios where "everything goes as well as it reasonably could", or named their "average case" scenarios.  And the two elicitations produced indistinguishable results.  And reality was usually slightly worse than the "worse case" scenario.  I *feel like* the "normal case" for AI alignment work required is being evaluated along much the same lines as "the best case / the case if every individual event goes as well as I imagine by default".

AI alignment could be super easy in theory and still take 50% more development time in practice; because that is a very normal thing to happen when somebody asks the project manager to make sure a piece of highly novel software *actually* has that "super easy" property the first time it's run under new conditions that can't be fully tested in advance.

"At least 50% more development time for the aligned AI project, versus the corner-cutting careless project, assuming both projects otherwise have access to the same stock of ideas and methods and computational resources" seems to me like an extremely probable and *normal* working assumption to make.

7wm.title: Meta-rules for (narrow) value learning are still unsolved
7wm.clickbait: We don't currently know a simple meta-utility function that would take in observation of humans and spit out our true values, or even a good target for a Task AGI.

7wp.title: Actual effectiveness
7wp.clickbait: If you want the AI's so-called 'utility function' to actually be steering the AI, you need to think about how it meshes up with beliefs, or what gets output to actions.
